   426→
   427→            <h2>Proof Strategy</h2>
   428→
   429→            <p>
   430→                The verification establishes that rotated roots and Chebyshev roots share identical power sums for all
   431→                positive degrees, which by Newton's identities implies they generate polynomials differing only by a
   432→                constant term. This approach reduces the geometric claim to an algebraic invariant (power sums), then
   433→                applies classical polynomial algebra to reach the conclusion.
   434→            </p>
   435→
   436→            <h3>Critical Proofs</h3>
   437→
   438→            <p>
   439→                <strong>Power Sum Invariance (<a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/PowerSums.html#powerSumCos_invariant" style="color: #3498db;">powerSumCos_invariant</a>):</strong>
   440→                The cornerstone of the entire proof. This establishes that ∑cos<sup>m</sup>(φ + 2πk/N) is independent of the
   441→                rotation angle φ for all m ≥ 1. The proof exploits the fact that cos(θ) = (e<sup>iθ</sup> + e<sup>-iθ</sup>)/2,
   442→                converting cosine powers into sums of complex exponentials. These exponential sums telescope to zero by discrete
   443→                orthogonality unless specific divisibility conditions hold, yielding the φ-independence. Without this result,
   444→                there would be no connection between rotated roots and Chebyshev polynomials.
   445→            </p>
   446→
   447→            <p>
   448→                <strong>Discrete Orthogonality (<a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/ChebyshevOrthogonality.html" style="color: #3498db;">ChebyshevOrthogonality module</a>):</strong>
   449→                Proves that ∑<sub>k=0</sub><sup>N-1</sup> exp(2πikm/N) = 0 for 0 < m < N and equals N when m = 0 or N divides m
   450→                (see <a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/ChebyshevOrthogonality.html#sum_exp_chebyshev_angles" style="color: #3498db;">sum_exp_chebyshev_angles</a>,
   451→                <a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/ChebyshevOrthogonality.html#sum_cos_chebyshev_angles_vanishes" style="color: #3498db;">sum_cos_chebyshev_angles_vanishes</a>).
   452→                This is the discrete analog of continuous Fourier orthogonality on the circle. The proof uses properties of
   453→                geometric series and the fact that N-th roots of unity satisfy ω<sup>N</sup> = 1. This orthogonality is what
   454→                causes most terms in the power sum expansion to vanish, leaving only the φ-independent contributions. It connects
   455→                harmonic analysis (orthogonality relations) to polynomial root behavior.
   456→            </p>
   457→
   458→            <p>
   459→                <strong>Newton's Identities (<a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/NewtonIdentities.html" style="color: #3498db;">NewtonIdentities module</a>):</strong>
   460→                Establishes the relationship between power sums of roots and elementary symmetric polynomials (coefficients)
   461→                via <a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/NewtonIdentities.html#multiset_newton_identity" style="color: #3498db;">multiset_newton_identity</a>.
   462→                Specifically, if two monic polynomials have roots with matching power sums S<sub>1</sub>, S<sub>2</sub>, ..., S<sub>N</sub>,
   463→                then the polynomials have identical coefficients except possibly the constant term
   464→                (<a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/NewtonIdentities.html#esymm_eq_of_psum_eq" style="color: #3498db;">esymm_eq_of_psum_eq</a>).
   465→                This is the bridge that converts power sum equality into polynomial equality up to a constant. The formalization handles the recursive structure
   466→                of Newton's identities and proves the converse direction needed: power sum agreement implies coefficient agreement.
   467→                This classical result from polynomial algebra is indispensable for connecting root properties to polynomial identity.
   468→            </p>
   469→
